Kennedy describes five archetypal relationships with the environment: the Eco-Engaged, often politically liberal, who have an acute level of concern about the environment, a moral commitment to protect it, and the conviction that an individual can make a difference; the Self-Effacing, who share the Eco-Engaged’s concerns but not the belief in their own efficacy; the Optimists, often politically conservative, who are confident in their relationship with the environment, doubt the severity of environmental problems, and resent insinuations that they don’t care; the Fatalists, who are pessimistic about environmental decline and feel little responsibility to adopt environment-friendly habits; and the Indifferent, who have no affinity for any part of the environmental movement.Kennedy argues that when liberals feel they have a moral monopoly on environmental issues, polarization results. If we are serious about protecting the planet, we must acknowledge that we don’t all need to care about the environment in the same way.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh  aActivism.  aAdult.  aAir pollution.  aAuction.  aBenefit corporation.  aCarbon footprint.  aCareer.  aChristie's.  aCivic engagement.  aCivil society.  aClimate change.  aCollege town.  aCompost.  aConservatism.  aConsumerism.  aCultural capital.  aCultural hegemony.  aCycling.  aDichotomy.  aDiego Rivera.  aEcofeminism.  aEcological crisis.  aEcological resilience.  aEcology.  aEcosystem.  aElectric car.  aEmployment.  aEnvironmental Values.  aEnvironmental economics.  aEnvironmental issue.  aEnvironmental justice.  aEnvironmental law.  aEnvironmental movement.  aEnvironmental organization.  aEnvironmental politics.  aEnvironmental protection.